Okay, so we need to find a function *k(x)* that makes this whole thing work.  

Think of it like this: if we plug something into *f(x)*, and then plug that result into *f(x)* again, we should get back what we started with.

For *x* greater than 3, *f(x)* is just *k(x)*. So, if we plug *k(x)* into *f(x)* again, we want to end up with *x*.  

That means *k(x)* has to be its own inverse! The only function that does that is *k(x) = x* itself.

So, for *x* greater than 3,  *k(x) = x*.

\[\boxed{k(x) =
\begin{cases}
x &\text{if }x>3, \\
\end{cases}
}\]

