Okay, so we've got two dice.  Each one has 6 sides, right? That means there are 6 times 6, or 36 different combinations you can roll.

To get a difference of zero, both dice have to show the same number. There are six ways that can happen: both ones, both twos, and so on up to both sixes.

So, the probability is 6 (the good outcomes) divided by 36 (all the possible outcomes). That simplifies to 1 out of 6. 


\begin{align*}
\boxed{\frac{1}{6}}
\end{align*}

