Okay, so we have 5 different balls and 3 different boxes.  Think of it like this: each ball can go in any of the three boxes.  

So the first ball has 3 choices, the second ball has 3 choices, and so on. That means we have 3 times 3 times 3 times 3 times 3, or 3 to the power of 5, which is 243.


\begin{equation*}
\boxed{243}
\end{equation*}

Okay, so we need to figure out how many rows in Pascal's Triangle have only even numbers except for maybe some 1's.

